            <!-- Beti Bachao Beti Padhao (BBBP) -->
            <div id="policy1" class="content-card show">
                <h3>Beti Bachao Beti Padhao (BBBP) Scheme</h3>
                <p>The BBBP scheme is a comprehensive program launched in January 2015 to address the declining Child Sex Ratio (CSR) and related issues of empowerment of women. It is a joint initiative of the Ministry of Women and Child Development, Ministry of Health and Family Welfare, and Ministry of Human Resource Development.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Objectives</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Prevent gender-biased sex selective elimination</li>
                        <li>Ensure survival and protection of the girl child</li>
                        <li>Ensure education and participation of the girl child</li>
                        <li>Challenge gender stereotypes and discriminatory social norms</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-check-circle feature-icon"></i> Key Features</h4>
                <p>The scheme focuses on multi-sectoral action in 100 selected districts (low on CSR) across the country. It includes:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Mass communication campaign to change societal mindset</li>
                    <li>Enabling girls' education through school enrollment drives</li>
                    <li>Linking cash transfer schemes to encourage girl child education</li>
                    <li>Strengthening implementation of Pre-Conception and Pre-Natal Diagnostic Techniques (PC&PNDT) Act</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line feature-icon"></i> Impact and Achievements</h4>
                <p>Since its launch, BBBP has shown significant impact:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Improvement in Sex Ratio at Birth (SRB) in many focus districts</li>
                    <li>Increased institutional deliveries and antenatal care registrations</li>
                    <li>Enhanced school enrollment and retention of girls</li>
                    <li>Greater awareness about legal rights of girls and women</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Access</h4>
                <p>The scheme operates through district administrations. For more information, visit the official website of the Ministry of Women and Child Development or contact your local Anganwadi center.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Mahila Shakti Kendra (MSK) -->
            <div id="policy2" class="content-card">
                <h3>Mahila Shakti Kendra (MSK) Scheme</h3>
                <p>Mahila Shakti Kendra (MSK) scheme was launched in November 2017 to empower rural women through community participation and skill development. The scheme aims to create an environment for women to realize their full potential.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Objectives</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Provide an interface for rural women to approach government</li>
                        <li>Offer skill development and employment opportunities</li>
                        <li>Promote digital literacy and health awareness</li>
                        <li>Create awareness about government schemes and programs</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-check-circle feature-icon"></i> Implementation Structure</h4>
                <p>The scheme operates at three levels:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>National Level:</strong> Policy making and technical support</li>
                    <li><strong>State Level:</strong> State Resource Centre for Women</li>
                    <li><strong>District/Block Level:</strong> Community engagement through student volunteers</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-users feature-icon"></i> Target Beneficiaries</h4>
                <p>The scheme primarily focuses on:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Rural women from marginalized communities</li>
                    <li>Adolescent girls (11-18 years) under Rajiv Gandhi Scheme</li>
                    <li>Pregnant women and lactating mothers</li>
                    <li>Women from SC/ST and other backward communities</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Access</h4>
                <p>MSK centers are established in rural areas. Women can visit these centers or contact local Anganwadi workers for information and support.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Pradhan Mantri Matru Vandana Yojana (PMMVY) -->
            <div id="policy3" class="content-card">
                <h3>Pradhan Mantri Matru Vandana Yojana (PMMVY)</h3>
                <p>PMMVY is a maternity benefit program launched in 2017 to provide partial compensation for wage loss and improve health seeking behavior among pregnant women and lactating mothers.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Benefits</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Cash incentive of ₹5,000 in three installments</li>
                        <li>Compensation for wage loss during pregnancy</li>
                        <li>Improved health and nutrition for mother and child</li>
                        <li>Encourages institutional delivery and immunization</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-money-bill-wave feature-icon"></i> Payment Structure</h4>
                <p>The scheme provides ₹5,000 in three installments:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>₹1,000 on early registration of pregnancy</li>
                    <li>₹2,000 after six months of pregnancy on receiving at least one ante-natal check-up</li>
                    <li>₹2,000 after child birth is registered and the child has received first cycle of vaccinations</li>
                </ol>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-check feature-icon"></i> Eligibility Criteria</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Pregnant women and lactating mothers (excluding those in regular employment)</li>
                    <li>For first live birth only</li>
                    <li>Beneficiaries must be 19 years or older</li>
                    <li>Must be Indian citizens</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Apply</h4>
                <p>Applications can be submitted at Anganwadi centers or approved health centers. Required documents include identity proof, bank account details, and pregnancy certificate.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Sukanya Samriddhi Yojana (SSY) -->
            <div id="policy4" class="content-card">
                <h3>Sukanya Samriddhi Yojana (SSY)</h3>
                <p>Launched in 2015 as part of the Beti Bachao Beti Padhao campaign, SSY is a small deposit savings scheme for girl children that offers attractive interest rates and tax benefits.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Features</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Higher interest rates than regular savings accounts</li>
                        <li>Tax benefits under Section 80C of Income Tax Act</li>
                        <li>Flexible deposit amounts with minimum ₹250 and maximum ₹1.5 lakh per year</li>
                        <li>Account can be opened at post offices and authorized banks</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-calendar-alt feature-icon"></i> Account Duration</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Account can be opened for girl child below 10 years</li>
                    <li>Account matures when girl turns 21</li>
                    <li>Partial withdrawal (up to 50%) allowed after age 18 for education/marriage</li>
                    <li>Account can be transferred anywhere in India</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-percentage feature-icon"></i> Current Benefits (2023)</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Interest Rate: 7.6% per annum (compounded annually)</li>
                    <li>Tax-free interest income</li>
                    <li>Tax-free maturity amount</li>
                    <li>No tax deduction at source (TDS)</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Open Account</h4>
                <p>Visit any post office or authorized bank with birth certificate of girl child, identity and address proof of guardian, and initial deposit amount.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- One Stop Centre (OSC) Scheme -->
            <div id="policy5" class="content-card">
                <h3>One Stop Centre (OSC) Scheme</h3>
                <p>Also known as Sakhi Centers, these are established under the Nirbhaya Fund to provide integrated support and assistance to women affected by violence, both in private and public spaces.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Services Provided</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Emergency medical assistance</li>
                        <li>Police assistance for FIR lodging</li>
                        <li>Psycho-social counseling</li>
                        <li>Legal aid and counseling</li>
                        <li>Temporary shelter (up to 5 days)</li>
                        <li>Video conferencing facility for court proceedings</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-map-marker-alt feature-icon"></i> Coverage</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Implemented in all districts across India</li>
                    <li>Centers located in government hospitals or district headquarters</li>
                    <li>24/7 helpline number (181) available</li>
                    <li>Services available to all women regardless of caste, class, religion etc.</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line feature-icon"></i> Impact</h4>
                <p>Since inception, OSCs have helped thousands of women by providing:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Immediate crisis intervention</li>
                    <li>Access to justice through legal support</li>
                    <li>Medical assistance and counseling</li>
                    <li>Rehabilitation and reintegration support</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Access</h4>
                <p>Women can directly approach any OSC center or call the women helpline number 181 for assistance and referral.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Ujjawala Scheme -->
            <div id="policy6" class="content-card">
                <h3>Ujjawala Scheme</h3>
                <p>Launched in 2007, Ujjawala is a comprehensive scheme to prevent trafficking of women and children for commercial sexual exploitation and to facilitate rescue, rehabilitation and reintegration of victims.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Scheme Components</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Awareness generation and community vigilance</li>
                        <li><strong>Rescue:</strong> Identification and rescue of victims</li>
                        <li><strong>Rehabilitation:</strong> Shelter, counseling, medical care</li>
                        <li><strong>Reintegration:</strong> Education, skill development, economic empowerment</li>
                        <li><strong>Repatriation:</strong> Cross-border victims assistance</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-home feature-icon"></i> Rehabilitation Services</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Immediate shelter through Protective and Rehabilitative Homes</li>
                    <li>Medical care including treatment for STDs, HIV/AIDS</li>
                    <li>Psychological counseling and psychiatric support</li>
                    <li>Legal support and court procedures assistance</li>
                    <li>Vocational training and skill development</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-users feature-icon"></i> Target Beneficiaries</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Women and children who are victims of trafficking</li>
                    <li>Women and children vulnerable to trafficking</li>
                    <li>Cross-border victims who are Indian nationals</li>
                    <li>Families of victims for preventive interventions</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Access Help</h4>
                <p>Contact local police, women helpline (181), Childline (1098) or approach any NGO working on anti-trafficking for assistance.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Mahila Police Volunteers (MPVs) -->
            <div id="policy7" class="content-card">
                <h3>Mahila Police Volunteers (MPVs) Scheme</h3>
                <p>The MPV initiative was launched to create a link between police and community to facilitate women in distress. MPVs act as an interface between police and the community to help women in need of assistance.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Roles</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Report incidents of violence against women</li>
                        <li>Create awareness about women's rights and schemes</li>
                        <li>Encourage women to report crimes without fear</li>
                        <li>Act as a bridge between community and police</li>
                        <li>Monitor and report on public spaces safety</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-shield feature-icon"></i> Selection and Training</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Volunteers selected from local communities</li>
                    <li>Preference given to women volunteers</li>
                    <li>Intensive training on gender issues and laws</li>
                    <li>Orientation on police procedures and support systems</li>
                    <li>Regular refresher training programs</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line feature-icon"></i> Impact</h4>
                <p>The scheme has helped in:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Increasing reporting of crimes against women</li>
                    <li>Building community trust in police systems</li>
                    <li>Early intervention in domestic violence cases</li>
                    <li>Creating safer public spaces for women</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Connect</h4>
                <p>MPVs operate at village/ward level. Contact your local police station or women helpline to connect with MPVs in your area.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Women Helpline Scheme -->
            <div id="policy8" class="content-card">
                <h3>Women Helpline Scheme (181)</h3>
                <p>The Women Helpline provides 24-hour emergency response to women affected by violence by linking them with appropriate authorities including police, hospitals, OSC, legal services etc.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Services Offered</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Immediate emergency response</li>
                        <li>Information about women related government schemes</li>
                        <li>Referral to appropriate authorities (police, hospitals etc.)</li>
                        <li>Crisis counseling</li>
                        <li>Legal information and guidance</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-phone-alt feature-icon"></i> Operation Details</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Toll-free number 181 available across India</li>
                    <li>24/7 availability in multiple languages</li>
                    <li>Caller's identity remains confidential</li>
                    <li>Follow-up mechanism for serious cases</li>
                    <li>Integrated with One Stop Centers and police</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line feature-icon"></i> Impact</h4>
                <p>The helpline has become a critical support system:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Thousands of distress calls addressed annually</li>
                    <li>Immediate assistance in emergency situations</li>
                    <li>Increased reporting of domestic violence cases</li>
                    <li>Better coordination between support services</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Use</h4>
                <p>Simply dial 181 from any phone (mobile/landline) anywhere in India to access free, confidential support.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Scheme for Adolescent Girls (SAG) -->
            <div id="policy9" class="content-card">
                <h3>Scheme for Adolescent Girls (SAG)</h3>
                <p>SAG aims at empowering out-of-school adolescent girls (11-14 years) through nutrition, life skills, and vocational training to help them become self-reliant.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Components</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Nutrition:</strong> Hot cooked meal or take-home ration</li>
                        <li><strong>Life Skills Education:</strong> Health, hygiene, rights</li>
                        <li><strong>Vocational Training:</strong> Basic skills development</li>
                        <li><strong>Iron & Folic Acid:</strong> Supplementation</li>
                        <li><strong>Health Check-ups:</strong> Regular monitoring</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-graduate feature-icon"></i> Target Group</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Out-of-school girls aged 11-14 years</li>
                    <li>Focus on girls from SC/ST communities</li>
                    <li>Girls from families below poverty line</li>
                    <li>Married girls in the age group</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line feature-icon"></i> Expected Outcomes</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Improved nutritional and health status</li>
                    <li>Enhanced awareness about health and rights</li>
                    <li>Reduction in early marriages</li>
                    <li>Better preparedness for adulthood</li>
                    <li>Increased self-confidence and decision-making ability</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Enroll</h4>
                <p>Contact your local Anganwadi center or Child Development Project Officer (CDPO) for enrollment details.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Working Women Hostel -->
            <div id="policy10" class="content-card">
                <h3>Working Women Hostel Scheme</h3>
                <p>This scheme promotes availability of safe and conveniently located accommodation for working women, with day care facilities for their children, to enable them to take up employment.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Features</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Safe and affordable accommodation for working women</li>
                        <li>Priority to women from rural areas, single mothers, etc.</li>
                        <li>Mandatory day care facility for children</li>
                        <li>Located near employment centers or transport hubs</li>
                        <li>Special provisions for women with disabilities</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-home feature-icon"></i> Facilities Provided</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Furnished living spaces with common facilities</li>
                    <li>Mess or cooking space</li>
                    <li>Day care center for children (up to 5 years)</li>
                    <li>Recreational facilities</li>
                    <li>Security measures including CCTV, guards</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-check feature-icon"></i> Eligibility</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Women employed in formal or informal sector</li>
                    <li>Students pursuing regular courses</li>
                    <li>Women undergoing training for employment</li>
                    <li>No income ceiling for single women/widows/divorcees</li>
                    <li>For married women, family income less than ₹50,000/month</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Apply</h4>
                <p>Applications can be made directly to hostel management. List of hostels available on Ministry of Women & Child Development website.</p>
            </div>
