            <!-- Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961 -->
            <div id="act1" class="content-card show">
                <h3>Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961</h3>
                <p>The Dowry Prohibition Act was enacted to prohibit the giving or taking of dowry in connection with marriages. It has been amended several times to strengthen its provisions.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Definition of dowry includes any property or valuable security given before, during or after marriage</li>
                        <li>Both giving and receiving dowry is punishable</li>
                        <li>Penalty: Minimum 5 years imprisonment and fine (minimum ₹15,000 or value of dowry, whichever more)</li>
                        <li>Demand for dowry is also punishable (2 years imprisonment + fine)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-shield feature-icon"></i> Protection Measures</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Dowry prohibition officers can be appointed to prevent dowry demands</li>
                    <li>List of presents to bride and bridegroom to be maintained</li>
                    <li>Burden of proof lies on the person accused of taking dowry</li>
                    <li>Special courts can be designated for speedy trial</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line feature-icon"></i> Recent Amendments</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Increased punishment and fines</li>
                    <li>Strict provisions against dowry demands</li>
                    <li>Provisions for protection of victims and witnesses</li>
                    <li>Mandatory reporting of dowry deaths</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Report</h4>
                <p>Approach local police station or women's cell to file complaint. Can also contact National Commission for Women helpline.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005 -->
            <div id="act2" class="content-card">
                <h3>Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005</h3>
                <p>This civil law provides protection to women from violence occurring within the family. It covers all women in domestic relationships - wives, mothers, sisters, live-in partners etc.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Definition of Domestic Violence</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Physical, sexual, verbal, emotional or economic abuse</li>
                        <li>Threats of such abuse</li>
                        <li>Harassment through unlawful dowry demands</li>
                        <li>Any other conduct harmful or injurious</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-shield-alt feature-icon"></i> Protection Measures</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Protection Orders:</strong> Prohibits respondent from committing violence</li>
                    <li><strong>Residence Orders:</strong> Ensures victim isn't thrown out of shared household</li>
                    <li><strong>Monetary Relief:</strong> For losses including medical expenses</li>
                    <li><strong>Custody Orders:</strong> Temporary custody of children</li>
                    <li><strong>Compensation Orders:</strong> For injuries/damages suffered</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-users feature-icon"></i> Implementation Structure</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Protection Officers appointed in each district</li>
                    <li>Service Providers (NGOs) registered to assist victims</li>
                    <li>Magistrates designated to hear cases</li>
                    <li>Medical facilities for examination and treatment</li>
                    <li>Shelter homes for temporary accommodation</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to File Complaint</h4>
                <p>Approach Protection Officer, Service Provider or directly to Magistrate. Can also seek help from women's helpline (181) or police.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- POSH Act, 2013 -->
            <div id="act3" class="content-card">
                <h3>Sexual Harassment at Workplace (Prevention, Prohibition & Redressal) Act, 2013</h3>
                <p>Commonly known as POSH Act, it provides protection against sexual harassment at workplace and for prevention and redressal of complaints.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Definition of Sexual Harassment</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Physical contact and advances</li>
                        <li>Demand or request for sexual favors</li>
                        <li>Sexually colored remarks</li>
                        <li>Showing pornography</li>
                        <li>Any other unwelcome physical, verbal or non-verbal conduct of sexual nature</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-building feature-icon"></i> Employer Responsibilities</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Form Internal Complaints Committee (ICC) at each office with 10+ employees</li>
                    <li>Display policy against sexual harassment at workplace</li>
                    <li>Organize awareness programs</li>
                    <li>Provide safe working environment</li>
                    <li>Assist in police investigation if needed</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-gavel feature-icon"></i> Redressal Mechanism</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Complaint to be made within 3 months (extendable)</li>
                    <li>ICC must complete inquiry within 90 days</li>
                    <li>Interim relief may be provided to complainant</li>
                    <li>Conciliation can be attempted before inquiry</li>
                    <li>Punishment may include written apology, warning, termination etc.</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to File Complaint</h4>
                <p>Approach your organization's ICC or Local Complaints Committee (for organizations with <10 employees). Can also approach police if it amounts to criminal offense.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Immoral Traffic Act, 1956 -->
            <div id="act4" class="content-card">
                <h3>Immoral Traffic (Prevention) Act, 1956</h3>
                <p>Also known as SITA, this act aims to prevent trafficking of women and girls for prostitution. It has been amended several times to strengthen provisions against sexual exploitation.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Prohibits running brothels or living on earnings of prostitution</li>
                        <li>Prevents soliciting in public places</li>
                        <li>Provides for rescue and rehabilitation of victims</li>
                        <li>Special courts for speedy trial</li>
                        <li>Protection of identity of victims</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-shield-alt feature-icon"></i> Protection Measures</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Protective homes for rehabilitation</li>
                    <li>Medical examination and treatment</li>
                    <li>Counseling and vocational training</li>
                    <li>Legal aid for victims</li>
                    <li>Special police units for enforcement</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle feature-icon"></i> Punishments</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Keeping brothel: 1-3 years imprisonment + fine</li>
                    <li>Living on earnings of prostitution: 2-5 years imprisonment + fine</li>
                    <li>Procuring/trafficking: 7 years to life imprisonment</li>
                    <li>Detaining someone in prostitution: 7 years to life imprisonment + fine</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Report</h4>
                <p>Contact local police, women helpline (181) or anti-trafficking NGOs. Can also approach special police units established under the Act.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Equal Remuneration Act, 1976 -->
            <div id="act5" class="content-card">
                <h3>Equal Remuneration Act, 1976</h3>
                <p>This act provides for payment of equal remuneration to men and women workers for same work or work of similar nature and prevents discrimination in employment.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Equal pay for equal work regardless of gender</li>
                        <li>No discrimination in recruitment, training, promotions etc.</li>
                        <li>Advisory committees to promote employment opportunities</li>
                        <li>Appointment of authorities to hear complaints</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-tie feature-icon"></i> Employer Responsibilities</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Maintain registers with details of employees and remuneration</li>
                    <li>Display notices regarding Act provisions</li>
                    <li>Comply with directions of authorities</li>
                    <li>Not to reduce remuneration to comply with Act</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-balance-scale feature-icon"></i> Redressal Mechanism</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Complaint to be made within 6 months (extendable)</li>
                    <li>Authorities can investigate complaints</li>
                    <li>Can direct payment of arrears of remuneration</li>
                    <li>Can impose penalties for non-compliance</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to File Complaint</h4>
                <p>Approach labor commissioner or equal remuneration officer in your area. Can also file complaint through trade unions or women's organizations.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Maternity Benefit Act, 1961 -->
            <div id="act6" class="content-card">
                <h3>Maternity Benefit Act, 1961</h3>
                <p>This act regulates employment of women in certain establishments for certain periods before and after childbirth and provides for maternity benefits.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Benefits</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Paid maternity leave of 26 weeks (8 weeks before delivery)</li>
                        <li>Medical bonus of ₹3,500 if no prenatal/natal care provided</li>
                        <li>Additional leave for miscarriage/illness</li>
                        <li>Protection against dismissal during leave</li>
                        <li>Work from home option after maternity leave</li>
                        <li>Crèche facility mandatory for establishments with 50+ employees</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-check feature-icon"></i> Eligibility</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Applies to establishments with 10+ employees</li>
                    <li>Women working for at least 80 days in 12 months preceding delivery</li>
                    <li>Covers all women employees including contractual</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle feature-icon"></i> Employer Responsibilities</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Not to employ women in hazardous work during pregnancy</li>
                    <li>Not to dismiss or give notice of dismissal during pregnancy</li>
                    <li>Pay maternity benefit at average daily wage rate</li>
                    <li>Provide nursing breaks until child is 15 months old</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Claim</h4>
                <p>Submit written notice to employer with medical certificate. In case of dispute, approach labor commissioner or file complaint in labor court.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Criminal Law Amendment, 2013 -->
            <div id="act7" class="content-card">
                <h3>Criminal Law (Amendment) Act, 2013</h3>
                <p>Enacted after the Nirbhaya case, this amendment introduced stricter laws for crimes against women including rape, sexual harassment, stalking, voyeurism etc.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Key Amendments</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Expanded definition of rape including non-penetrative acts</li>
                        <li>New offenses: Acid attacks, stalking, voyeurism</li>
                        <li>Increased punishment for rape (minimum 7 years, up to life imprisonment)</li>
                        <li>Death penalty for rape causing death or persistent vegetative state</li>
                        <li>Faster trials with time-bound investigations</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-shield-alt feature-icon"></i> Victim Protection Measures</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Recording statement by woman police officer</li>
                    <li>Medical examination with victim's consent</li>
                    <li>In-camera trials to protect victim's identity</li>
                    <li>No character questioning of victim</li>
                    <li>Compensation through victim compensation schemes</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle feature-icon"></i> Punishments</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Rape: Minimum 7 years, maximum life imprisonment</li>
                    <li>Gang rape: Minimum 20 years, maximum life imprisonment</li>
                    <li>Rape of minor: Minimum 20 years, maximum death penalty</li>
                    <li>Acid attack: Minimum 10 years, maximum life imprisonment</li>
                    <li>Stalking/Voyeurism: Up to 7 years imprisonment</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Report</h4>
                <p>File FIR at nearest police station. Can also approach women's helpline (181) or One Stop Centers for assistance in filing complaint.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

