        <div class="col-lg-8">
            <!-- Right to Life & Security -->
            <div id="right1" class="content-card show">
                <h3>Right to Life, Liberty and Security of Person</h3>
                <p>This fundamental right, enshrined in Article 21 of the Indian Constitution, ensures that every woman has the inherent right to live with dignity, free from violence and threats to her life and personal liberty.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Constitutional Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Article 21: Protection of life and personal liberty</li>
                        <li>Article 14: Right to equality before law</li>
                        <li>Article 15: Prohibition of discrimination on grounds of sex</li>
                        <li>Article 19: Freedom of movement and residence</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-shield-alt feature-icon"></i> Legal Protections</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Domestic Violence Act, 2005 for protection within homes</li>
                    <li>Indian Penal Code provisions against violence (Section 354, 375, 376 etc.)</li>
                    <li>Protection from sexual harassment at workplace (POSH Act)</li>
                    <li>Right to self-defense under Indian law</li>
                    <li>Right to approach courts for protection (writ jurisdiction)</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-hands-helping feature-icon"></i> Implementation Mechanisms</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Women police stations and help desks</li>
                    <li>24/7 women helpline (181)</li>
                    <li>One Stop Centers for crisis management</li>
                    <li>Fast track courts for crimes against women</li>
                    <li>Legal aid services through National Legal Services Authority</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>In case of any threat to life or security, immediately contact police (100) or women helpline (181). Can also approach courts for protection orders.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Right to Equality -->
            <div id="right2" class="content-card">
                <h3>Right to Equality</h3>
                <p>This fundamental right ensures that women are treated equally in all spheres of life - social, economic, political and cultural - without any discrimination based on gender.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Constitutional Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Article 14: Equality before law</li>
                        <li>Article 15: Prohibition of discrimination on grounds of sex</li>
                        <li>Article 16: Equality of opportunity in public employment</li>
                        <li>Article 39: Equal pay for equal work</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-balance-scale feature-icon"></i> Legal Protections</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Equal Remuneration Act, 1976 for equal pay</li>
                    <li>Maternity Benefit Act for workplace equality</li>
                    <li>Hindu Succession Act for property rights</li>
                    <li>Special provisions for women in local governance (73rd & 74th Amendments)</li>
                    <li>Reservation for women in educational institutions</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line feature-icon"></i> Implementation Mechanisms</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>National Commission for Women to address grievances</li>
                    <li>Women's cells in police departments</li>
                    <li>Gender budgeting in government schemes</li>
                    <li>Affirmative action programs for women</li>
                    <li>Public awareness campaigns on gender equality</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>In case of discrimination, file complaint with National/State Commission for Women or approach courts. For workplace discrimination, approach ICC or labor authorities.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Right to Non-Discrimination -->
            <div id="right3" class="content-card">
                <h3>Right to Non-Discrimination</h3>
                <p>This right ensures that women cannot be discriminated against on the basis of their gender in any sphere of life including employment, education, healthcare, property rights etc.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Constitutional Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Article 15: Prohibits discrimination on grounds of sex</li>
                        <li>Article 16: Equality of opportunity in public employment</li>
                        <li>Article 39: Equal pay for equal work</li>
                        <li>Article 42: Just and humane conditions of work</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-gavel feature-icon"></i> Legal Protections</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Equal Remuneration Act, 1976</li>
                    <li>Maternity Benefit Act, 1961</li>
                    <li>Prohibition of sexual harassment at workplace (POSH Act)</li>
                    <li>Hindu Succession Act (amended 2005) for equal inheritance rights</li>
                    <li>Special Marriage Act allowing inter-caste/religion marriages</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-users feature-icon"></i> Protected Areas</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Employment:</strong> Recruitment, promotions, benefits</li>
                    <li><strong>Education:</strong> Admissions, scholarships, facilities</li>
                    <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Access to medical services</li>
                    <li><strong>Property:</strong> Ownership and inheritance</li>
                    <li><strong>Public Services:</strong> Access to government schemes</li>
                    <li><strong>Public Spaces:</strong> Equal access and safety</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>File complaints with National/State Commission for Women or appropriate authorities (like labor commissioner for workplace discrimination). Can also approach courts for violations.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Right to Education -->
            <div id="right4" class="content-card">
                <h3>Right to Education</h3>
                <p>This right ensures that all women and girls have equal access to quality education without any discrimination. The Right to Education Act, 2009 makes education a fundamental right for children aged 6-14 years.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Constitutional Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Article 21A: Right to free and compulsory education (6-14 years)</li>
                        <li>Article 15: Prohibition of discrimination in educational institutions</li>
                        <li>Article 46: Promotion of educational interests of weaker sections</li>
                        <li>Article 51A(k): Fundamental duty of parents to educate children</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-school feature-icon"></i> Legal Protections</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Right to Education Act, 2009 for free elementary education</li>
                    <li>National Policy on Education with focus on girls' education</li>
                    <li>Schemes like Beti Bachao Beti Padhao, Sukanya Samriddhi Yojana</li>
                    <li>Reservation for girls in educational institutions</li>
                    <li>Prohibition of discrimination in admissions</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-chalkboard-teacher feature-icon"></i> Government Initiatives</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Kasturba Gandhi Balika Vidyalayas for girls from marginalized communities</li>
                    <li>National Scheme of Incentives to Girls for Secondary Education</li>
                    <li>Free bicycles for girl students in many states</li>
                    <li>Girls' hostels for higher education</li>
                    <li>Special coaching for competitive exams</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>If denied admission or facing discrimination, approach school management committee, district education officer or file complaint with State Commission for Protection of Child Rights.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Right to Health -->
            <div id="right5" class="content-card">
                <h3>Right to Health</h3>
                <p>This right ensures that women have access to comprehensive, quality healthcare services throughout their life cycle, including reproductive health services.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Constitutional Basis</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Article 21: Right to life includes right to health</li>
                        <li>Article 47: Duty of state to improve public health</li>
                        <li>Article 15(3): Special provisions for women and children</li>
                        <li>Article 39(e): Health protection for workers</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-medkit feature-icon"></i> Key Components</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Reproductive Health:</strong> Maternal care, family planning</li>
                    <li><strong>Nutrition:</strong> Special programs for adolescent girls, pregnant women</li>
                    <li><strong>Disease Prevention:</strong> Immunization, screening for diseases</li>
                    <li><strong>Mental Health:</strong> Counseling and psychiatric care</li>
                    <li><strong>Occupational Health:</strong> Protection from workplace hazards</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-hospital feature-icon"></i> Government Programs</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Janani Suraksha Yojana for safe motherhood</li>
                    <li>Pradhan Mantri Matru Vandana Yojana for pregnant women</li>
                    <li>Ayushman Bharat for health insurance coverage</li>
                    <li>Mission Indradhanush for immunization</li>
                    <li>National Mental Health Program</li>
                    <li>National Nutrition Mission (Poshan Abhiyan)</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>Access services at government health centers. In case of denial or poor quality services, file complaint with hospital authorities, health department or State Human Rights Commission.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Right to Property -->
            <div id="right6" class="content-card">
                <h3>Right to Property</h3>
                <p>This right ensures that women have equal rights to own, inherit and dispose of property. The Hindu Succession Act (amended 2005) gives daughters equal rights in ancestral property.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Legal Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Hindu Succession Act, 1956 (amended 2005): Equal inheritance rights</li>
                        <li>Indian Succession Act, 1925: For Christians, Parsis</li>
                        <li>Muslim Personal Law: Inheritance as per Shariat</li>
                        <li>Special Marriage Act, 1954: Property rights in inter-religion marriages</li>
                        <li>Dowry Prohibition Act: Dowry as woman's exclusive property</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-home feature-icon"></i> Types of Property Rights</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Inheritance Rights:</strong> Equal share in ancestral property</li>
                    <li><strong>Marital Property:</strong> Rights in matrimonial home</li>
                    <li><strong>Dowry Property:</strong> Exclusive rights over dowry items</li>
                    <li><strong>Acquired Property:</strong> Full rights over self-acquired property</li>
                    <li><strong>Agricultural Land:</strong> State laws govern inheritance</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-balance-scale feature-icon"></i> Legal Remedies</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>File partition suit for ancestral property</li>
                    <li>Approach family court for matrimonial property disputes</li>
                    <li>File police complaint for dowry harassment</li>
                    <li>Seek injunction orders to prevent property alienation</li>
                    <li>Approach civil court for declaration of rights</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>For property disputes, consult a lawyer to file appropriate civil suit. Can also approach State Commission for Women or Legal Services Authority for free legal aid.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Right to Movement -->
            <div id="right7" class="content-card">
                <h3>Right to Freedom of Movement</h3>
                <p>This fundamental right ensures that women can move freely throughout the territory of India, reside and settle in any part of the country, and practice any profession.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Constitutional Provisions</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Article 19(1)(d): Freedom to move freely throughout India</li>
                        <li>Article 19(1)(e): Freedom to reside and settle in any part</li>
                        <li>Article 19(1)(g): Freedom to practice any profession</li>
                        <li>Article 21: Right to life and personal liberty</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-map-marked-alt feature-icon"></i> Legal Protections</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>No restrictions based on marital status</li>
                    <li>Right to choose place of residence</li>
                    <li>Right to travel domestically and internationally</li>
                    <li>Protection against unlawful confinement</li>
                    <li>Right to work anywhere in the country</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-shield-alt feature-icon"></i> Government Initiatives</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Safe transportation options for women</li>
                    <li>Women-only compartments in public transport</li>
                    <li>Working women hostels in cities</li>
                    <li>GPS tracking in public transport vehicles</li>
                    <li>Emergency response systems for women in distress</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>In case of any restriction on movement, approach police or file habeas corpus petition in High Court. For safety concerns, use women helpline (181) or safety apps.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Right to Privacy -->
            <div id="right8" class="content-card">
                <h3>Right to Privacy</h3>
                <p>Recognized as a fundamental right by the Supreme Court in 2017, this right protects women's personal autonomy, bodily integrity and private life from unwarranted intrusion.</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye feature-icon"></i> Constitutional Basis</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Article 21: Right to life and personal liberty</li>
                        <li>Article 19(1)(a): Freedom of speech and expression</li>
                        <li>Article 14: Right to equality</li>
                        <li>Justice K.S. Puttaswamy judgment (2017): Recognized privacy as fundamental right</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-user-secret feature-icon"></i> Key Aspects</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Bodily Autonomy:</strong> Right to make reproductive choices</li>
                    <li><strong>Data Privacy:</strong> Protection of personal information</li>
                    <li><strong>Marital Privacy:</strong> Protection from marital rape (pending legislation)</li>
                    <li><strong>Digital Privacy:</strong> Protection from online harassment</li>
                    <li><strong>Medical Privacy:</strong> Confidentiality of health records</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-gavel feature-icon"></i> Legal Protections</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Information Technology Act provisions against cyber crimes</li>
                    <li>Protection from voyeurism under Criminal Law Amendment</li>
                    <li>Medical Termination of Pregnancy Act provisions for privacy</li>
                    <li>POSH Act provisions for confidentiality in complaints</li>
                    <li>Domestic Violence Act provisions for protection orders</li>
                </ul>

                <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle feature-icon"></i> How to Exercise This Right</h4>
                <p>In case of privacy violations, file police complaint or approach courts. For online harassment, report to cyber crime cell. Seek injunction orders for intrusive behavior.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
